<!-- ───── EDITORIAL BODY ───── -->
<div class="editorial" data-screen-label="04 Editorial">
  <!-- 01 — OVERVIEW -->
  <section class="section" id="overview">
    <aside class="section-head-col">
      <span class="ornament">❧</span>
      <div class="num">I.</div>
      <div class="label">The case in brief</div>
      <h2>What is BPC-157, and why is it discussed?</h2>
      <p class="marginalia"><strong>Editor's note.</strong> The discussion has outpaced the data. A 2025 systematic review found one human trial — but you wouldn't know that from social media.</p>
    </aside>

    <div class="section-body">
      <div class="prose">
        <p>BPC-157 is a synthetic, 15-amino-acid <strong>pentadecapeptide</strong> derived from a protective protein found in human gastric juice. It has been studied since 1991, almost entirely in rodent models, where it is associated with accelerated wound healing, tendon repair, and protection of the gastric mucosa.<a class="cite" href="#ref-1">001</a></p>
        <p>In the popular literature, BPC-157 is widely discussed as a recovery peptide. In the peer-reviewed literature, it is something narrower: a candidate with a coherent rodent mechanism story and a sparse human evidence base.<a class="cite" href="#ref-2">002</a> A 2025 systematic review of 36 studies found only <strong>one published clinical study</strong> — the early Croatian PL-14736 work on inflammatory bowel disease, which was halted before Phase 3.<a class="cite" href="#ref-6">006</a></p>
        <p>This entry distills the strongest preclinical findings, the open questions, and a quality-rubric for reading new BPC-157 papers as they appear.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="pullquote">
        "Preclinical evidence is consistent and replicable. Human evidence is — at the time of writing — almost entirely absent."
        <span class="attribution">— Kwan, Wong et al. · JAMA Network Open · 2025</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 02 — MECHANISM -->
  <section class="section" id="mechanism">
    <aside class="section-head-col">
      <span class="ornament">❧</span>
      <div class="num">II.</div>
      <div class="label">Mechanism of action</div>
      <h2>Four proposed mechanisms.</h2>
      <p class="marginalia">All derived from rodent or in-vitro work. No receptor specific to BPC-157 has yet been identified.</p>
    </aside>

    <div class="section-body">
      <div class="mech-row">
        <div class="mech" data-mech="1">
          <span class="roman">i.</span>
          <div class="head">
            <span class="icon">
              <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M3 12c4-7 14-7 18 0M3 12c4 7 14 7 18 0M9 12a3 3 0 116 0 3 3 0 01-6 0z"/></svg>
            </span>
            <span class="name">Angiogenesis</span>
          </div>
          <p>Up-regulates VEGFR-2 and stimulates new blood-vessel formation at injury sites — the most replicated rodent finding.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="mech" data-mech="2">
          <span class="roman">ii.</span>
          <div class="head">
            <span class="icon">
              <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M4 4l4 8-4 8M20 4l-4 8 4 8M8 12h8"/></svg>
            </span>
            <span class="name">NO modulation</span>
          </div>
          <p>Interacts with the nitric-oxide system, bidirectionally — depending on the L-NAME / L-arginine state.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="mech" data-mech="3">
          <span class="roman">iii.</span>
          <div class="head">
            <span class="icon">
              <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="8"/><path d="M12 4v4M12 16v4M4 12h4M16 12h4"/></svg>
            </span>
            <span class="name">Cytoprotection</span>
          </div>
          <p>Protects gut, liver and brain cells from NSAID-, alcohol- and ischemia-induced damage in rodent models.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="mech" data-mech="4">
          <span class="roman">iv.</span>
          <div class="head">
            <span class="icon">
              <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M4 20l4-4 4 4 4-4 4 4M4 12l4-4 4 4 4-4 4 4"/></svg>
            </span>
            <span class="name">Growth-factor cross-talk</span>
          </div>
          <p>Modulates EGR-1 and FAK / paxillin signalling — a candidate explanation for tendon-repair effects.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="pathway">
        <div class="label">i. VEGFR-2 pathway · angiogenic</div>
        <div class="pathway-chain">
          <span class="node input">BPC-157</span>
          <span class="arrow">→</span>
          <span class="node">VEGFR-2 ↑</span>
          <span class="arrow">→</span>
          <span class="node">NO ↑</span>
          <span class="arrow">→</span>
          <span class="node target">Vascular sprouting</span>
        </div>
        <div class="pathway-result"><strong>Net effect.</strong> Increased capillary density at injury sites in rodent tendon and muscle.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="pathway">
        <div class="label">iv. EGR-1 / FAK pathway · tendon repair</div>
        <div class="pathway-chain">
          <span class="node input">BPC-157</span>
          <span class="arrow">→</span>
          <span class="node">EGR-1 ↑</span>
          <span class="arrow">→</span>
          <span class="node">FAK / paxillin</span>
          <span class="arrow">→</span>
          <span class="node target">Collagen organisation</span>
        </div>
        <div class="pathway-result"><strong>Net effect.</strong> Improved tensile strength and fibre alignment in transected Achilles tendon models.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

