  <!-- 04 — COUNTER-EVIDENCE -->
  <section class="section" id="counter">
    <aside class="section-head-col">
      <span class="ornament">❧</span>
      <div class="num">IV.</div>
      <div class="label">Counter-evidence</div>
      <h2>Where the case weakens.</h2>
      <p class="marginalia">A research catalogue is only as honest as its dissent. These are the strongest reasons to doubt the BPC-157 story.</p>
    </aside>

    <div class="section-body">
      <div class="objection-list">
        <div class="objection">
          <span class="num">i.</span>
          <div class="body">
            <h4>The literature clusters around a single research group.</h4>
            <p>Roughly two thirds of BPC-157 papers originate from the Zagreb / Sikiric laboratory or its direct collaborators. Independent replication outside this cluster is sparse and, where attempted, has produced smaller effect sizes.</p>
            <span class="src">Kwan &amp; Wong, 2025 · JAMA Network Open</span>
          </div>
          <span class="severity" data-level="high">High concern</span>
        </div>

        <div class="objection">
          <span class="num">ii.</span>
          <div class="body">
            <h4>No specific receptor has been identified.</h4>
            <p>After 30+ years of investigation, there is no characterised BPC-157 receptor. Mechanism claims rely on downstream markers (VEGFR-2, EGR-1, FAK) rather than direct binding studies — unusual for a peptide with this much published work.</p>
            <span class="src">Vukojevic, 2022 · Neural Regen Res</span>
          </div>
          <span class="severity" data-level="high">High concern</span>
        </div>

        <div class="objection">
          <span class="num">iii.</span>
          <div class="body">
            <h4>The PL-14736 Phase 2 trial was halted before completion.</h4>
            <p>The only published human program (Croatia, IBD, sponsored by Pliva Pharmaceuticals) was discontinued before Phase 3. The reasons were not publicly disclosed in detail — commercial, regulatory, and efficacy explanations all remain on the table.</p>
            <span class="src">Veljaca et al., 2003 · Gastroenterology</span>
          </div>
          <span class="severity" data-level="moderate">Moderate</span>
        </div>

        <div class="objection">
          <span class="num">iv.</span>
          <div class="body">
            <h4>Effect sizes in some rodent papers strain biological plausibility.</h4>
            <p>Several BPC-157 tendon-repair studies report restorative effects that exceed any approved comparator drug — a pattern more consistent with measurement bias or unblinded outcome assessment than with a uniquely powerful intervention.</p>
            <span class="src">Multiple Achilles-transection rodent studies, 2011–2019</span>
          </div>
          <span class="severity" data-level="moderate">Moderate</span>
        </div>

        <div class="objection">
          <span class="num">v.</span>
          <div class="body">
            <h4>Long-term safety is genuinely unstudied.</h4>
            <p>No published data exists for continuous BPC-157 use beyond ~8 weeks in humans. Cumulative dose, immunogenicity, and effects after discontinuation are open empirical questions — not a benign default.</p>
            <span class="src">No human long-term data on file</span>
          </div>
          <span class="severity" data-level="open">Open question</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

